The filter for queued issues runs when workGraph loads, but uses $wip.queuedIssues which may not be populated yet. Result: filter uses empty set, queued issues appear in both places.

**Fix:** Make the reactive statement depend on $wip so it re-runs when queued data loads:
```javascript
// Change from:
$: if ($workGraph && !$workGraph.error) {
// To:
$: if ($workGraph && !$workGraph.error && $wip) {
```

**File:** web/src/routes/work-graph/+page.svelte line 74

## Problem

When following an orchestrator (tmux tab switch), Work Graph shows blue 'new issue' fade on ALL issues, not just truly new ones. This creates visual noise and makes the highlight meaningless.

**Root cause:** `previousIssueIds` tracks issues from the previous fetch, but isn't reset on project switch. When `orchestratorContext.project_dir` changes, all issues from the new project appear 'new' because they weren't in the old project's set.

**Location:** `web/src/routes/work-graph/+page.svelte` lines 137-155, 161-169

## Solution

1. **Track seen issues per-project** - Change from `Set<issueId>` to `Map<projectDir, Set<issueId>>`
2. **Persist to localStorage** - So page refresh doesn't re-trigger highlights for already-seen issues  
3. **Only highlight truly new issues** - Issues created after the timestamp when user first saw this project, not just 'not in previous fetch'

**Implementation approach:**

```typescript
// Instead of:
let previousIssueIds = new Set<string>();

// Use:
const SEEN_ISSUES_KEY = 'work-graph-seen-issues';

interface SeenIssuesState {
  byProject: Record<string, {
    issueIds: string[];
    firstSeenAt: string; // ISO timestamp
  }>;
}

// Load from localStorage on mount
// Only highlight issues created after firstSeenAt for this project
// Update localStorage on each fetch
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Switching orchestrator tabs doesn't trigger blue fade on existing issues
- [ ] Page refresh doesn't trigger blue fade on already-seen issues
- [ ] Truly new issues (created after first viewing project) still get blue fade
- [ ] Different projects maintain separate 'seen' state

## References

- Recent fix attempt: `e61778c0 fix: preserve expansion state across rebuilds and fix highlight on children`
- Polling config: `555d4259 feat: reduce polling interval to 5s and extend highlight to 30s`

Create unified `ProcessedIssueCache` that consolidates three fragmented dedup mechanisms.

## Problem

Daemon has 3 separate dedup layers with gaps:
1. **SpawnedIssueTracker** - in-memory, 6h TTL, lost on restart
2. **SessionDedupChecker** - OpenCode only, doesn't see Claude CLI
3. **HasPhaseComplete** - beads comments, parsing can fail

Gap: Completed work can respawn after daemon restart or 6h TTL expiration.

## Solution

Create `pkg/daemon/processed_cache.go`:

```go
type ProcessedIssueCache struct {
    // Persistent storage (JSONL file)
    // Single entry point for all dedup checks
}

func (c *ProcessedIssueCache) ShouldProcess(beadsID string) bool {
    // 1. Check persistent cache (survives restart)
    // 2. Check OpenCode sessions
    // 3. Check beads comments for Phase: Complete
    // Returns false if ANY check says 'already processed'
}

func (c *ProcessedIssueCache) MarkProcessed(beadsID string) {
    // Add to persistent cache with timestamp
}
```

## Implementation

1. Create `~/.orch/processed-issues.jsonl` for persistent state
2. Load on daemon start
3. Single `ShouldProcess()` entry point replaces 3 separate checks
4. Prune entries older than 30 days on load

## Success Criteria

- [ ] Daemon restart doesn't lose dedup state
- [ ] No respawns of Phase: Complete issues
- [ ] Single code path for all dedup checks

